Hey writefag - Don't get too worried about it. ...makes the flow tend to dry up, and the frustration sets in.

First and foremost, how far into your story are you, and what do you want to so with it? If it's a quick romp, especially a lewd one, there's absolutely nothing wrong with writing in the first or second person (especially if you're writing it as a story recanted by the protagonist or as a present tense play-by play). The strength here is that it lets your readers enjoy some vivid self insertion JOI fun. If your looking to do a narrative focused story, 3rd person past is usually best (even if the narrator turns out to be one of the main characters in the end). It's the standard for most novels for a reason, and is waaaaaay easier to write well.

If you're just looking to knock something out quick, it might behoove you to press on through with what you've got. Look to the finish line for your motivation here.

If you like the characters and setting enough that you want to expand it, you can always kick off a new work with the old universe and characters. Hell, you can even let the earlier standalone work be a preamble of sorts.

Last but not least, you can always just do a quick rewrite of the story, changing the tense and POV but keeping all the dialogue and details the same. This can actually go pretty damn quick. Just know that it can put you in an editing mood. ...sometimes it can take a few days to transition back into creative writing mode.

Best of luck to you, whatever path you wind up choosing.

I'll address these in random order

>a quick rewrite of the story, changing the tense and POV
for the interested, that takes about half the time as the original draft. Once you start re-writing to fit the other POV character's thoughts, all bets are off.

>press on through with what you've got
There's a point where you have to stop and admit that there's going to be a rewrite and it would be better to review what can be salvaged. On the other hand, I've mentioned in the past that doubt is part of the workflow. In my case, I write, add detail the next day, and add more detail and polish on the third. Learn from the doubt, but don't let it take up the entirety of your writing.

>first person vs. second vs. third
I'll debate this for the sake of writers that are going to start. First & third are easy to write as long as you keep what the characters or narrator knows straight. A third person omniscient is easy because you have no restrictions. My opinion, made stronger by the money/mouth engine, is that POV is determined more by what the writer wants to hide than anything else. Second person works nicely when you want to get the reader to agree with something by tacit, and then twist the knife.

Here's some thoughts for longer pieces like what mine could have ended up being
Ask three general questions. If your characters are fully formed enough in your head, they will tell you an answer. While they may be lying their asses off, it's still a clue.
Force them into a personality test. I used one of the attempts to clone myers-briggs online. Behold, one of my male chars and female chars were way too similar. Use two different tests, and make them justify each answer. Yes, this took a couple nights, but it's scary how quick you can flesh out motivations this way.
Oblique Strategies.
Have a drink, or whatever. Just enough to relax and drop the ego and inner naysayer. Rip out a thousand words, get a good night's sleep, read your progress in 24 hours

Quoted By: >>26926886 >>26928496
>>26924346
Try thinking about characters and their pasts. Likes, dislikes, fashion, hobbies, parents, friends, places they live, etc. It doesn't have to be as fleshed out as that, but if you try to take into account everything that made them who they are, they'll be more easy to write dialogue for.
An exercise you can do is try writing the two characters you want dialogue between (or more) fighting over something simple, like where to eat or what to watch on TV if applicable. Try to think how they would react then. How far they would take it, what they would do, and what they prefer.

Hopefully that helps some. Dialogue should come as naturally as possible.
